metadata.name: Deep Thoughts #57
metadata.description:
There are times when we think about something, we just go deeper and deeper, and soon we find ourselves in a position that we can't stop thinking about it.

While sometimes this may be enjoyable or even good for us, we should also never forget that, some depths have no coming back.

* * *

Due to the use of very thin line strokes, there's a slight difference between how other browsers display the output, compared to Firefox. The intended output is the Firefox version, but you can enjoy and capture (S) Deep Thoughts in whichever version you prefer.

Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas

metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #165
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: CR Art Sessions //1 #29
metadata.description:
In Argentina there is a very young and talented music producer called BIZARRAP.

He is very famous for the BZRP Music Sessions, which are tracks in collaboration with international artists that Bizarrap produces in his studio, which also serves as a recording studio for the official video clip of the track.

In these sessions the artists have the freedom to express themselves in ways that perhaps the industry doesn't allow them because they have an image to sell, or the freedom to deliver whatever they want.

For example, in the Music Session with Nicky Jam, the Puerto Rican artist sings rap in Spanish, English and reggaeton, all in the same song.

Inspired by this concept I decided to launch my CR Art Sessions format. The idea is to take previous works and reconvert them or give me the freedom to play with the algorithms and explore new options and parameters to reach their limits or to obtain something different but with the same essence.

The CR Art Sessions //1 is based on my first fx(hash) project called Geoetris. 

The same algorithm was slightly modified to produce 3 different types of art that the user will be able to visualize. 
1. The first type is an extreme version of the Geoetris project, where the parameters were modified to have blend between the pieces and generate many more elements on screen. 
2. The second is a composition of circles and squares, where there is a very simple rule that can only sometimes be broken and that is that the rectangles start in the middle of the circle. 
3. The third is a version where the larger geometric shapes are not filled and only their silhouette is marked.

-----

Reserves: All 'Geoetris' owners and 40-40 slots for 'Yo automata' and 'Isomeric Doppelgangers' owners

-----

Royalties: 50% to minter

-----

Controls:

Explore each art variant with the '1', '2', '3' keys

The 'e' key exports the current canvas

The 's' key exports the image in 3200x4000 px resolution

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2022)

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: MoodColors #120
metadata.description: The artwork is based on principles of Orphism and Bauhaus , as one of the most striking examples of a combination of functionality, simplicity and at the same time the ability to convey the underlying meaning, where the form is determined by function. Where color is one of the most important values. Our goal is to visualize all the richness and versatility of human emotions with the help of color. What, if not color, is able to convey the whole gamut of feelings and experiences that we experience.  Every bright event in our life, both positive and negative, always leaves its mark in our memory. We show it through lines – it's like wrinkles on the face, marks of the experience, like a note on a sheet, a dash / tick, like an entry in the diary of life, where the sheet on which we made a note is colored in the color of emotions and sensations that we experienced again and again. It's always a lot of mixed shades that have their own unique palette.  The fundamental emotions and feelings such as anger, sadness, fear, disgust, joy and love are taken. Each token is one emotion, where with the help of color we show how multifaceted it can be.

metadata.name: Scaffold #36
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: Balancium #281
metadata.description:
"Balancium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

In the fall of 1931, in Alexander Calder's studio, Marcel Duchamp coined the term 'mobile' for his kinetic sculptures. Later, Calder wrote: "This, in French, means not only 'movable'— but also a 'motive', 'a reason for an act' so I found it a very good word."
 
Around the same year, Bruno Munari started making colorful and whimsical mobiles. He called them "useless machines", existing without any purpose and inviting viewers to just look. Elements are connected with nearly invisible threads or wires, allowing the artist to create the illusion of shapes floating in the air.

Balancium is both a virtual mobile and a useless object. Generated by the code, it undergoes a continual transformation. The movement of the air, or invisible fluid, becomes an integral part of the design and amplifies serenity. 
 
There is a keyboard key that unlocks more variations.

metadata.name: Relic #59
metadata.description: This is my 3rd project on fxhash! I was inspired by some black and white circle art and tried to mimic the techniques. From there, my own taste and creativity took over. This is the result. There are 3 shapes - circle, square, and triangle, and 3 colors - pink, blue, and gold. Each work can have multiple layers or "rings" going outwards. Each layer is subdivided randomly and can have pieces missing. This produces some interesting results! Often surprising and sometimes delightful. They look like ancient "relics" to me, so hence the name :) Please enjoy.

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #17
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Relic #136
metadata.description: This is my 3rd project on fxhash! I was inspired by some black and white circle art and tried to mimic the techniques. From there, my own taste and creativity took over. This is the result. There are 3 shapes - circle, square, and triangle, and 3 colors - pink, blue, and gold. Each work can have multiple layers or "rings" going outwards. Each layer is subdivided randomly and can have pieces missing. This produces some interesting results! Often surprising and sometimes delightful. They look like ancient "relics" to me, so hence the name :) Please enjoy.

metadata.name: Sketch A #46
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch A starts very simple. It's the basic grid framework I intend to use for the series. It's just a simple grid with one colored square (usually). Colors are borrowed from Echos/Orbits. Grid size, padding, and line thickness vary.
